# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antje-hermenau
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] General elections were held in East Germany on 18 March 1990.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] These were the first free elections held in the region since the turbulent Weimar days of 1932 and would become the only truly democratic vote in the German Democratic Republic (GDR).
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The election stood as a final verdict on four decades of one-party rule by the Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED)–led National Front.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] It took place against the backdrop of the German reunification process, which had already begun to gather momentum.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The contest was swept by the Alliance for Germany, a coalition led by the newly reconstituted East German Christian Democratic Union (CDU), which captured 192 of the 400 seats in the Volkskammer and had run on a promise of swift reunification with West Germany.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD), re-established only months earlier after its forced 1946 merger with the Communist Party of Germany (KPD), was widely tipped to win but instead came second with 88 seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In third was the former ruling SED, now rebranded as the Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS), which secured 66 seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The Alliance fell just short of an outright majority having needed 201 seats to govern alone.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Lothar de Maizière, the CDU's leader, invited the SPD to join a broad coalition alongside the German Social Union (DSU) and Democratic Awakening (DA).
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The SPD hesitated, wary of the DSU's right-wing populist tone, having earlier vowed to collaborate with all but the PDS and DSU.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] However, a grand coalition was ultimately formed.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This government, commanding a two-thirds supermajority in the Volkskammer, set about the task of dismantling the East German state and laying the legal groundwork for reunification, although the coalition would collapse later that August.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] On 3 October 1990, the GDR ceased to exist and all its territories joined the Federal Republic of Germany (FRG).
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] 144 Volkskammer members were integrated into the West German Bundestag, serving until the all-German federal election on 2 December that year.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The Peaceful Revolution of 1989 resulted in the Socialist Unity Party of Germany giving up its monopoly on power, and permitting opposition parties to operate for the first time.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] They began to form in large numbers throughout November and December 1989.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Opposition groups formed the East German Round Table, which was joined by representatives of the SED to negotiate reforms; at its first meeting on 7 December 1989, the Round Table agreed that elections to the Volkskammer would be held on 6 May 1990.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] On 20 February 1990 the Volkskammer passed a new electoral law, reducing it in size to 400 members elected via party-list proportional representation, with no electoral threshold.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Joint lists between parties were allowed, and a number of parties formed alliances for the election, including the Association of Free Democrats, Alliance 90, and an alliance between the Green Party and Independent Women's Association.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Seats were calculated nationally using the largest remainder method, and distributed in multi-member constituencies corresponding to the fifteen *Bezirke*.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The campaign for was unusually short, lasting only seven weeks after the vote was brought forward from May to 18 March following negotiations between the Round Table and the government of Hans Modrow on 28 January.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This tight schedule posed significant organizational challenges.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Only the PDS, as the successor to the SED, possessed the necessary infrastructure and financial resources for a full campaign.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In contrast, newly formed opposition parties and civil rights groups were still defining their platforms and had minimal experience in electioneering.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Their shortcomings were partially mitigated by substantial support from West German parties, which provided logistical and strategic assistance to their Eastern counterparts.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Western support facilitated the creation of several electoral alliances.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The CDU partnered with the German Social Union and Democratic Awakening to form the Alliance for Germany.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The FDP backed the Association of Free Democrats, which included the Liberal Democratic Party of Germany (LDPD) and the minor FDP of the GDR.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] These alliances were established only weeks before the election, relying heavily on Western assistance such as the CDU's "district partnerships" and the participation of West German campaigners.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] At the outset, the SPD appeared likely to win, benefiting from historical roots in the region and strong backing from the West German SPD.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Early polls showed it leading with 54 percent support, ahead of the PDS and CDU.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Despite early advantages, the SPD's momentum declined as reunification became the dominant issue.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] West German SPD leader Oskar Lafontaine was cautious about unification and criticized possible NATO membership for a united Germany, which may have weakened the party's appeal.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Meanwhile, Helmut Kohl and the Western CDU made unification the central theme of their campaign, drawing large crowds to rallies in cities such as Erfurt and Chemnitz.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The Alliance for Germany organised over 1,400 campaign events and mobilised high-profile Western politicians.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In a final blow to the opposition, Democratic Awakening's lead candidate Wolfgang Schnur was exposed by *Der Spiegel* as a Stasi informant just days before the vote, damaging the credibility of one of the key parties in the alliance.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The Alliance for Germany presented its election manifesto under the slogan "Never again socialism" (*„Nie wieder Sozialismus“*).
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Its main objectives included achieving German reunification based on the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany as a unified constitution, guaranteeing rights to private property and unrestricted freedom of trade, and removing all barriers to Western investment.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The alliance called for the immediate introduction of the Deutsche Mark at a 1:1 exchange rate to the East German mark.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Social policy commitments included establishing a social security network, environmental protection measures, securing energy supplies, and harmonising laws with the West, notably abolishing criminal offences linked to political activities.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Other priorities were monument preservation, education reform, maintaining day nurseries, restoring the federal states (*Länder*), and ensuring press freedom.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] At the first party conference of the re-established SPD, held in Leipzig from 22 to 25 February 1990, the party adopted its basic programme and election manifesto centred on the promotion of an ecologically oriented social market economy.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The PDS campaign was titled "Democratic Freedom for All – Social Security for Everyone".
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] It characterised itself as a democratic socialist party advocating a socially and ecologically oriented market economy that ensured social security based on merit.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The PDS emphasised preserving the GDR's social achievements under the SED, including the right to work, childcare systems, cooperative and public ownership in the economy, and values of anti-fascism and internationalism.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The programme demanded disarmament of both East and West and supported maintaining the status of former SED members and land reforms.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Rejecting immediate unification, the PDS proposed a confederal structure between East and West Germany, preserving their separate statehood while gradually moving towards a neutral and demilitarised German confederation.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The elections, while a landmark of democratic transformation, were also shaped significantly by external influences particularly from West Germany.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Writer Michael Schneider was among those who criticised what he viewed as overwhelming interference by West German politicians and institutions.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In his work, he described the campaign environment as one saturated with West German personalities, party activists and messaging.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] West German political parties, especially its branches of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and Social Democratic Party (SPD), sent campaigners and resources across the border to bolster their East German affiliates.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] According to Schneider, taxpayer funds from West Germany were used to support this mobilisation, raising questions about the balance of influence and the fairness of the electoral playing field.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Civil rights activist and co-founder of the New Forum, Jens Reich, echoed these concerns from the perspective of the East German opposition.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Speaking two decades after the vote, he reflected that the entire West German political apparatus had been transplanted into the East, overwhelming grassroots democratic movements that had played a key role in the Peaceful Revolution.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In his words, "The Bonn hippopotamus came in such a mass that you were simply helpless." Reich observed that the election campaign bore little resemblance to a homegrown democratic process and instead felt like a western-style election exported wholesale into a fragile new democracy.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This imbalance, he argued, made it difficult for indigenous East German parties and civic movements to compete on equal terms.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This large-scale West German involvement was not limited to campaign workers and funding.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] West German media, political advertisements and party materials flooded East German spaces in the run-up to the election, promoting a vision of rapid reunification under Western terms.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] While many East Germans were eager for economic stability and political freedom, critics argue that this form of campaigning blurred the lines between support and manipulation.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The West German framing of the vote as a *de facto* referendum on reunification placed enormous pressure on the East German electorate and marginalised alternative visions for East Germany's future.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Although the election was formally free, the conditions surrounding it raise ongoing debate over whether it represented a fully sovereign exercise in democracy or a lopsided contest shaped by the overwhelming influence of West Germany.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In 2005 Forschungsgruppe Wahlen researcher Matthias Jung, who was involved in organising opinion polling for the election, spoke of the difficulties of the task.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] He attributed this to the unpredictable behaviour of the electorate as well as the total lack of infrastructure and methods for gauging public opinion, which forced the institute to build an entirely new polling model.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Despite beginning work at the end of 1989, FW only released one poll before the election, which Jung claimed accurately predicted the CDU victory.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This may refer to a FW poll showing that 35% of voters believed an Alliance for Germany-led government would be most capable of solving the country's problems, while only 27% believed an SPD-led government would; 29% believed a grand coalition would be most capable.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This starkly contrasted with other polls, conducted without reliable methods, which predicted a landslide SPD victory.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] In order to determine the composition of the East German representatives in the Bundestag between German reunification and the first post-reunification elections in December 1990, the results of the 1990 Volkskammer election were recounted, using the new states of Germany as constituencies.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] This was possible since the original election results were declared on the Kreis level, and the states were re-established by simply amalgamating Kreise together.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The results in each Kreis forming a state were summed up to determine the statewide result.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The recount fixed the number of Volkskammer members from each party who would be co-opted into the Bundestag.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The newly elected Volkskammer was constituted on 5 April 1990, and elected Sabine Bergmann-Pohl of the CDU as its president.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] As the State Council of the GDR was dissolved at the same time, she became East Germany's interim head of state.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Four days later, after protracted negotiations, Lothar de Maizière announced the formation of a grand coalition between the Alliance for Germany, SPD, and BFD.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] On 12 April 1990, he was elected Prime Minister of the GDR by the Volkskammer with 265 votes in favour, 108 against, and 9 abstentions.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The partners in the coalition commanded a two-thirds supermajority in the Volkskammer, making it an übergroß coalition with enough seats to pass amendments to the constitution.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] On 21 June, the Volkskammer formed a special committee, chaired by Joachim Gauck, to control the dissolution of the Ministry for State Security (Stasi).
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] On 20 September 1990, the Volkskammer voted 299–80 to accept the Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany, which had earlier been approved in a 442–47 vote by the West German Bundestag.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The treaty stipulated that East Germany would unify its territory with Federal Republic of Germany via Article 23 of the Basic Law, meaning that East Germany and the Volkskammer would cease to exist.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The chamber's last legislative period therefore only lasted four and a half months.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The treaty took effect on 3 October 1990; on the same day, 144 of the 400 Volkskammer deputies became members of the Bundestag (63 from the CDU, 33 from the SPD, 24 from the PDS, 9 from the BFD, 8 from the DSU, and 7 from Alliance 90 and the Green Party).
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The 8 DSU members joined the CDU/CSU Bundestag Group, briefly renamed CDU/CSU/DSU.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] The distribution of seats between these parties was determined by recalculating the results of the 1990 elections on a per-state basis.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-east-german-general-election] Their tenure came to an end two months later with the first all-German federal election on 2 December 1990.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-saxony-state-election] The **1990 Saxony state election** was held on 14 October 1990 to elect the members of the first Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-saxony-state-election] It was the first election held in Saxony since the reunification of Germany, which took place on 3 October.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-saxony-state-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) led by Kurt Biedenkopf dominated the election with 53.8% of the vote, followed by the Social Democratic Party (SPD) with 19.1%.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-saxony-state-election] Biedenkopf subsequently became Saxony's first post-reunification Minister-President.
[src:antje-hermenau/1990-saxony-state-election] The table below lists parties which won seats in the election.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 16 October 1994 to elect the members of the 13th Bundestag.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU alliance led by Helmut Kohl remained the largest faction in parliament, with Kohl remaining Chancellor in a narrowly re-elected coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] This elected Bundestag was the largest in history until 2017, numbering 672 members.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Even though this election did not lead to a switch in government, it saw the election of many people to the Bundestag who would play an important role later.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Future CDU leaders Friedrich Merz and Armin Laschet were first elected to the Bundestag in 1994, as were future cabinet ministers Norbert Röttgen and Peter Altmaier.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] This was the last election until 2009 that a centre-right government was elected.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) let its members elect a candidate for chancellor against Helmut Kohl after SPD leader Björn Engholm and chancellor candidate-designate had to resign in 1993 amid scandal.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Rudolf Scharping, Minister-President of Rhineland-Palatinate, beat Gerhard Schröder and Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul in the SPD's internal election.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Scharping was only elected with 40 percent of the vote and relied on campaigning with other SPD leaders and rivals such as Oskar Lafontaine and Gerhard Schröder, both self-confident and outspoken, in a "troika".
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Tension between them greatly hurt his campaign.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] In addition, Scharping was seen as a weak leader due to his lack of charisma and media skills, and therefore did not induce a lot of enthusiasm.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] For the first time in their existence, Alliance 90/The Greens seemed to be willing to join a government in case a centre-left SPD–Greens coalition had a workable majority in the Bundestag.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] The election also saw a "red socks" campaign used by the centre-right, including the CDU/CSU and the Free Democratic Party (FDP), to scare off a possible red–red–green coalition (SPD–Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS)–Greens).
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Analysts have stated that such a strategy likely paid off, as it was seen as one of the decisive elements for the narrow victory of Kohl for the CDU/CSU–FDP.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] The campaign was criticized as an obvious attempt to discredit the whole political left; the PDS reinterpreted it for itself by printing red socks.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] The coalition between the CDU/CSU and the FDP was able to continue in power with Helmut Kohl as chancellor.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] The PDS won four constituency seats in its power base of the former East Berlin, qualifying it for proportional representation even though the party won 4.4 percent of the vote, just short of the 5% electoral threshold required for full parliamentary status.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit regional parties, any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-german-federal-election] This was the first time in the history of the Federal Republic that the FDP was not the third-largest party in the chamber.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-saxony-state-election] The **1994 Saxony state election** was held on 11 September 1994 to elect the members of the 2nd Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-saxony-state-election] The incumbent Christian Democratic Union (CDU) government led by Minister-President Kurt Biedenkopf retained its majority and continued in office.
[src:antje-hermenau/1994-saxony-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 1st Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The **2004 Saxony state election** was held on 19 September 2004 to elect the members of the 4th Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The incumbent Christian Democratic Union (CDU) government led by Minister-President Georg Milbradt lost its majority.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The CDU subsequently formed a grand coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD), and Milbradt was re-elected as Minister-President.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The Far Right National Democratic Party of Germany (NPD) won 12 seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] This is the first time since the 1960s that the party had seats in a state parliament.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 3rd Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The most striking result of the election was the entrance of the far-right National Democratic Party (NPD) into the Landtag with 12 seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The party's support was concentrated in the rural areas; commentators attributed its success to alienation stemming from economic depression.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The continuing strength of the SED successor party, the Party of Democratic Socialism, which again was the second largest party, was also notable.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The CDU remained the largest party with 55 of 124 seats, but lost its majority, forcing it to find coalition partners.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The most logical was the classical liberal Free Democratic Party, who entered the Landtag in the election, but a CDU–FDP government would be one seat short of the necessary majority.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] Cooperation with the PDS or The Greens was ideologically unfeasible.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] A theoretical alliance between the CDU and NPD would hold a majority, but this was out of the question.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The result was a grand coalition CDU and SPD.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] This government outcome was later mirrored in the 2005 federal election.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] The CDU's Georg Milbradt remained in office as Minister-President.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] Notably, the NPD received two more votes on the ballot for Minister-President than it had members in the Landtag.
[src:antje-hermenau/2004-saxony-state-election] It is presumed that two CDU Landtag members backed the NPD as a protest against the grand coalition.
[src:antje-hermenau/2009-saxony-state-election] The **2009 Saxony state election** was held on 30 August 2009 to elect the members of the 5th Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2009-saxony-state-election] The incumbent grand coalition of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Minister-President Stanislaw Tillich retained its majority.
[src:antje-hermenau/2009-saxony-state-election] However, the CDU chose to discontinue the coalition in favour of forming government with the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:antje-hermenau/2009-saxony-state-election] Tillich was subsequently re-elected as Minister-President.
[src:antje-hermenau/2009-saxony-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 4th Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The **2014 Saxony state election** was held on 31 August 2014 to elect the members of the 6th Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The incumbent coalition government of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and Free Democratic Party (FDP) led by Minister-President Stanislaw Tillich was defeated as the FDP lost all its seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The CDU subsequently formed a grand coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD), and Tillich was re-elected as Minister-President.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] After the 2009 state election, held a month before the 2009 federal election, the CDU–SPD grand coalition left office and was replaced by a CDU-led coalition with the FDP.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The FDP suffered a major decline in support nationally after 2009, culminating in their ejection from the Bundestag in the 2013 federal election.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Thus, in the lead-up to the 2014 state election, the Saxony state government was the only government nationwide that included the FDP.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] It seemed unlikely this coalition could continue after the election, as polling indicated the FDP may not even pass the 5% threshold to enter the Landtag.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The largest opposition party was The Left.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Polling indicated that a coalition between The Left, the SPD and The Greens may have been able to secure a majority, but this option was rejected by both the SPD and the Greens prior to the election.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] For the SPD, the state election in Saxony was their second electoral test (after the European elections) since becoming the junior partner in the federal grand coalition.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Polls suggested that the public viewed the SPD's role in government as positive; issues that had been worked on by the government were primarily election promises of the SPD.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Despite this, all polls showed that the SPD was headed for another third-place finish in the state election.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The SPD's election campaign was centred on their lead candidate, Martin Dulig, who involved his family in the campaign.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Dulig was also supported by former federal Chancellor Gerhard Schröder.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) was hoping to win seats in a state parliament for the first time.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] In both the 2013 federal election and the 2014 European elections, AfD had achieved its strongest results in Saxony (6.8% in the federal election and 10.1% in the European elections).
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The National Democratic Party (NPD) had won seats in Saxony in 2004 and retained them, with losses, in 2009.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Polling and election results for the NPD had trended downwards since then, with most polls suggesting the party would not cross the 5% threshold and would thus lose their representation.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The Pirate Party won 1.9% of the vote in the previous state election.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Despite polling in late 2011 and 2012 showing its support up to as much as 9% in Saxony, the party lost most of its popularity throughout 2013, and the party had averaged around 2% in Saxony since the end of the year.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Polls suggested that the CDU would again be the largest party.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Minister-President Tillich was therefore expected to lead coalition negotiations.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] In addition to the SPD, the Greens hoped for a coalition with the CDU, but a "black-green" coalition was considered unlikely because the Greens oppose coal mining in Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Prior to the election, Tillich was open to coalitions with the FDP, the SPD, the Greens or AfD.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Carsten Linnemann, the chairman of the CDU/CSU Business Association, stated that a coalition with the Greens was a viable alternative if the FDP did not obtain any seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Tillich did not rule out a coalition with AfD, though CDU general-secretary Peter Tauber spoke out against the possibility.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The Left was unlikely to overtake the CDU, according to polls.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The party wanted to form a coalition with the SPD in particular.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The SPD, however, were sceptical about such an arrangement.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The NPD was not considered in coalition discussions.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 5th Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Due to the ejection of the FDP from the Landtag, the CDU was forced to seek new coalition partners.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Minister-President Tillich ruled out a coalition with AfD.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] The CDU held exploratory talks with the Greens and the SPD.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Talks with the Greens were inconclusive; the Greens claimed that education policy and energy policy were the sticking points.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Antje Hermenau, the Greens' lead candidate, then resigned on 20 September.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] Coalition talks began on 19 September between the CDU and the SPD.
[src:antje-hermenau/2014-saxony-state-election] On 9 November 2014, the SPD announced that 82.2% of its members had voted in favour of the coalition agreement between the CDU and SPD.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Antje Hermenau was born on 3 July 1964, in Leipzig, the daughter of a housewife and a metalworker, and grew up in modest circumstances.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She did not attend kindergarten or after-school care.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She describes her childhood as free and independent, and experienced this time as formative.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Thomas Extended Secondary School (EOS) in Leipzig and began studying to become a teacher of German and English at the Karl Marx Leipzig University that same year.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] During her studies, she worked part-time as a night watchwoman to become financially independent from her parents.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] With her diploma thesis on *political vocabulary in the CSCE process*, Hermenau earned her teaching degree in 1989.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She then worked as a teacher at the 4th Secondary School in Leipzig.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In 1990, she married the American David Rush.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] From 2000 to 2002, she pursued a part-time degree in administrative sciences at the German University of Administrative Sciences Speyer, graduating with a master's degree.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She has not yet taken up a teaching position in the Saxon public service .
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] After resigning from all political offices in September 2014, Hermenau registered a small business as a political consultant in Dresden.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] On 4 June 2016, Hermenau was elected Vice President of the Association of German-Language Speechwriters.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] The events of the fall of the Berlin Wall and subsequent reunification politicized the Rush family.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] While her husband was active in the Democracy Now movement, Antje Rush became involved with the Green Party in East Germany.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In February 1990, she took over the Green Party's seat on the Leipzig Round Table, where she met, among others, Wolfgang Tiefensee.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She ran unsuccessfully for Leipzig City Council in the first free local elections in East Germany on 6 May 1990.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Subsequently, she was the only woman involved in the founding of a Saxon state branch of the Green Party.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] At the founding assembly of the Green Party's state branch in Freiberg in September 1990, she was elected to the tenth spot on the joint list of the New Forum, other citizens' movements, and the Greens.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] There she also met future members of the Landtag of Saxony, Klaus Gaber and Kornelia Müller.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the first Saxony state elections on 14 October 1990, the joint list achieved 5.6% of the vote and ten seats.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] This made Rush the youngest of the Forum's ten parliamentary group members, who entered the first Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Within the parliamentary group, led by Klaus Gaber, she focused on education policy issues in Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the election for the Saxon state list for the 1994 German federal election, Antje Rush was elected to second place behind Werner Schulz.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] After Alliance 90/The Greens failed to re-enter the state parliament on 11 September 1994, with 4.1% of the list votes, the party received 4.8% of the Saxon list votes in the election for the 13th German Bundestag five weeks later.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] The Saxon state association of Alliance 90/The Greens was entitled to send two representatives, and Hermenau became a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] There, she served on the Budget Committee.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In 1998, Hermenau again entered the German Bundestag via the top spot on the Saxon Greens' state list.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Once again, she was a member of the Budget Committee.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the 2004 Saxony state election, she was the lead candidate for the Green Party.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] During the election campaign, in which Alliance 90/The Greens focused on environmental issues, school and university policy, and culture, Antje Hermenau represented the Green Party's state association.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Under the slogan "Saxony's Green Power Woman: Antje Hermenau," the Saxon Greens pursued a form of personalization in their state election campaign.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] With this election, the Green Party in Saxony, with 5.1% of the list votes (6 seats), succeeded in returning to the Saxon State Parliament.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Among other things, the early and relatively uncontroversial agreement on Hermenau as the lead candidate and her commitment to relinquish her seat in the Bundestag upon entering the State Parliament are considered several factors in the Greens' success.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Monika Lazar from the district of Leipzig took over the vacated seat in the Bundestag.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] On 10 June 2007, Antje Hermenau presented the idea of a collective tax cut for all women .
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She argued that it could offset the average income deficit of women in Germany.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] According to her, this was a form of "positive discrimination," which was preferable to negative discrimination.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the state election on 30 August 2009, Alliance 90/The Greens, with their lead candidate Antje Hermenau, achieved 6.4 percent of the vote (9 seats).
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Antje Hermenau was re-elected as parliamentary group leader.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] For her statement, "If I wanted to discuss anything with the Saxony FDP on an equal footing, I would have to lie flat on the floor," Hermenau was awarded the quote of the year at the State Press Conference's summer party on 17 June 2010.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the state election on 31 August 2014, in which the Greens received 5.7% of the vote, she was her party's lead candidate.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Subsequently, on 4 September 2014, she announced her withdrawal from the race for parliamentary group leadership, a position she had held since 2004.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] After a state party conference on 20 September 2014, voted against entering into coalition negotiations with the CDU Saxony following two exploratory talks, she announced her withdrawal from active politics.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] She explained her decision by stating that she considered it wrong for the Greens to position themselves as a left-wing party and to reject the black-green option, which the state association had campaigned on.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Together with mayor of Grimma Matthias Berger, Hermenau has been a prominent figure in the new "Citizens' Movement for Saxony" since autumn 2018, a self-described political "centrist movement".
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the 2019 Saxony state election, she unsuccessfully ran for the Free Voters of Saxony in 20th place on their list for the Landtag of Saxony.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Since leaving politics, she has worked as an author and political consultant for organizations and companies.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] In the fall of 2015, she published a polemical essay entitled *The Future Will Be Different* on global issues of social and economic development.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] A year later, she attracted attention by giving a reading from her book at an event organized by the AfD.
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Tobias Heimbach, among others, wrote in the daily newspaper Die Welt that there had been “outraged reactions on social media".
[src:antje-hermenau/antje-hermenau] Hermenau justified her willingness to engage in dialogue with the AfD by saying that a democracy thrives on dialogue, which the then-chairman of the Bündnis 90/Die Grünen Sachsen Jürgen Kasek, described as “political prostitution by enemies of democracy.
